        <h2 id="deposit">Deposit</h2>

        <h3>Who can deposit</h3>

        <p>We accept deposits from affiliates of Columbia University, Barnard College, Jewish Theological Seminary, Teachers College, and Union Theological Seminary.</p>

        <ul>
          <li>Current faculty and staff</li>
          <li>Emeritus faculty</li>
          <li>Retired faculty (still in directory?)</li>
          <li>Students may deposit their theses or capstone projects with the approval of their degree program. Some programs encourage or require students to deposit theses in Academic Commons. Students may also be able to deposit other work. For more information, see the section on <a href="#student-works">student works</a>, below.</li>
          <li>Departments, centers, and programs</li>

        </ul>

        <h3>Eligible content</h3>

        <h4>Results of research and scholarship</h4>
        <p>Academic Commons accepts research and scholarship created at Columbia and its affiliate institutions.</p>

        <h4>Deposit agreement</h4>
        <p>As part of the deposit process, you sign an agreement that grants Columbia University a non-exclusive license to distribute your work in the repository. By signing this agreement, you affirm that you hold sufficient rights to grant this license to Columbia.  </p>

        <p>Logged-in depositors sign the deposit agreement once. The agreement applies to all subsequent deposits.</p>

        <ul>
          <li>Read our <%= link_to 'copyright information', '#copyright' %> to learn more.</li>
          <li>Read about managing copyrights to your work by visiting the <a href="https://copyright.columbia.edu">Copyright Advisory Services</a> website.</li>
        </ul>

        <h4>Shareable “as is”</h4>
        <p>Your deposit should be ready to share online “as is.” If you create a new version of the work at a later date, you can deposit the new version as well. We will retain both versions and create links between them in repository metadata.</p>

        <h4>Protects privacy and confidentiality</h4>
        <p>Deposited works must be in compliance with all relevant federal, state, and institutional policies and guidelines regarding the protection of the privacy and confidentiality of human subjects. Works that should not be openly available online should not be deposited in Academic Commons.</p>

        <h3>File formats</h3>

        <h4>All file types accepted</h4>
        <p>We accept any type of file, though we encourage depositors to use formats which are non-proprietary and can be opened and used in a variety of platforms and applications (for example, a csv file is preferable to one in Excel).</p>

        <h4>Files larger than 100MB</h4>
        <p>Our self-deposit form accepts individual files up to 100MB. If you have larger files to deposit, contact us and we will arrange an alternative method of transfer.</p>

        <h4>Deposit fee for files over 10GB</h4>
        <p>You can deposit individual files up to 10GB free of charge. There is a one-time fee of $5 per GB for individual files that are over 10GB and up to 100GB in size. This fee is payable at the time of deposit. If you have individual files larger than 100GB, please contact us.</p>

        <h3>How to deposit</h3>

        <h4>Log in to Academic Commons with your UNI</h4>
        <p>If you have a Columbia UNI, you can log in and follow the instructions on how to deposit.</p>

        <h4>Email us</h4>
        <p>Contact us at <a href="mailto:ac@columbia.edu">ac@columbia.edu</a> if you:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>have questions.</li>
          <li>want to deposit a file larger than 100MB.</li>
          <li>want to make a proxy deposit.</li>
          <li>want to arrange for an ongoing deposit of works such as student theses or working papers.</li>
        </ul>

        <p>If you deposit via email, please note that we will ask you to sign our deposit agreement if you have not already done so.</p>

        <h3>Your work in the repository</h3>

        <h4>Deposit timeline</h4>
        <p>Please allow up to a week for your deposit to become available in Academic Commons. Email us at <a href="mailto:ac@columbia.edu">ac@columbia.edu</a> if you have any questions or need to request faster processing. If you have a Columbia UNI you will receive an automatic email notification when your work is available in the repository.</p>

        <h4>Persistent identifier for each work</h4>
        <p>Each work in Academic Commons is assigned a DIgital Object Identifier (DOI), which is a type of persistent URL. A sample DOI is: 10.7916/D8ZS2W8R. DOIs expressed as URLs look like this: https://doi.org/10.7916/D8ZS2W8R. Use the DOI when citing or referring to a work in Academic Commons.</p>

        <h4>Usage statistics reports</h4>
        <p>Authors who provide a Columbia UNI will receive a monthly email showing the number of views and downloads for each of their works in Academic Commons. Contact us at <a href="mailto:ac@columbia.edu">ac@columbia.edu</a> if you are not receiving our monthly emails or if you would like us to forward the emails to a new address.</p>

        <h4>Changing works in the repository</h4>
        <p>We do not change or replace files that have already been made available in Academic Commons. However we can archive a new version of a work and link it to older versions.</p>

        <h4>Removing works from the repository</h4>
        <p>We strongly discourage the withdrawal of works from Academic Commons. However, you can request that public access to your work in Academic Commons be disabled. Though the work will no longer be publicly accessible, some metadata about the work will remain publicly available in Academic Commons.</p>

